Hello Steven,

My name is Ian and I will be assisting you with your case.

Unfortunately we do not have a way to mark errors or warnings as known and filter them out.
If you'd like I can open an enhancement request for this and our product teams may be able to implement it in a future version.



Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom

TextBody:
Hello Steven,

You can exclude the directories that are giving you problems like this in the FSAA. FSAC. amd SEEK system scans.
To do this, open the job and navigate to configuration and select the query. From the right pane double click on the query and you will see the query properties open.



Once you have the query properties open, select configure and from the Data Collector wizard navigate to scoping options and select Add



From the scoping options window you will add the resource name and host name and select either share or folder exclude from the drop down.
The screenshot below would be an example of how you would exclude the share that is casing the error you provided to me.



Below is the full documentation on the SEEK scan options, if you have any questions please let me know and I'd be happy to assist.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/AccessAnalyzer_12.0/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Solutions/FileSystem/Collection/1-SEEK_System_Scans.htm

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
Senior Technical Support Engineer
__________________ _________
Powerful Data Security Made Easy
6160 Warren Parkway, Suite 100, Frisco, TX 75034
www.netwrix.com

Hello Steven,

You can exclude the directories that are giving you problems like this in the FSAA. FSAC. amd SEEK system scans.
To do this, open the job and navigate to configuration and select the query. From the right pane double click on the query and you will see the query properties open.



Once you have the query properties open, select configure and from the Data Collector wizard navigate to scoping options and select Add



From the scoping options window you will add the resource name and host name and select either share or folder exclude from the drop down.
The screenshot below would be an example of how you would exclude the share that is casing the error you provided to me.



Below is the full documentation on the SEEK scan options, if you have any questions please let me know and I'd be happy to assist.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/AccessAnalyzer_12.0/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Solutions/FileSystem/Collection/1-SEEK_System_Scans.htm

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
Senior Technical Support Engineer

www.netwrix.com

Hello Steven,

You can exclude the directories that are giving you problems like this in the FSAA. FSAC. amd SEEK system scans.
To do this, open the job and navigate to configuration and select the query. From the right pane double click on the query and you will see the query properties open.



Once you have the query properties open, select configure and from the Data Collector wizard navigate to scoping options and select Add



From the scoping options window you will add the resource name and host name and select either share or folder exclude from the drop down.
The screenshot below would be an example of how you would exclude the share that is casing the error you provided to me.



Below is the full documentation on the SEEK scan options, if you have any questions please let me know and I'd be happy to assist.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/AccessAnalyzer_12.0/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Solutions/FileSystem/Collection/1-SEEK_System_Scans.htm

Subject: RE: Netwrix Support Ticket #442164 -  - Omit errors from scan jobs    [ ref:!00D70091pB.!500Qk0O5DQE:ref ]

TextBody:
Hello Steven,

Thank you for your time and patience on this issue and I am glad that we were able to get your issue resolved for you. 
The following is a summary of the ticket for your records.

Issue:
Scan jobs are throwing errors on file system objects that errors are expected on. Need to filter these objects to clear the errors.


Resolution:
Added exclusions to the objects that are expected to error using scoping option documentation.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/AccessAnalyzer_12.0/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Admin/DataCollector/FSAA/ScopingOptions.htm

At this time I will be closing your ticket out for you. This case can be re-opened at any time if any related issues return. 
Please feel free to reach out to the Netwrix team if you have any additional questions or would like assistance with any issues. Following this email, you will receive an automated confirmation that the case has been closed.
You will also receive a survey link, it would help us greatly to improve our support service if you could provide any feedback that you may have regarding your experience with this case.

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
Senior Technical Support Engineer

Hello Steven,

You can exclude the directories that are giving you problems like this in the FSAA. FSAC. amd SEEK system scans.
To do this, open the job and navigate to configuration and select the query. From the right pane double click on the query and you will see the query properties open.



Once you have the query properties open, select configure and from the Data Collector wizard navigate to scoping options and select Add



From the scoping options window you will add the resource name and host name and select either share or folder exclude from the drop down.
The screenshot below would be an example of how you would exclude the share that is casing the error you provided to me.



Below is the full documentation on the SEEK scan options, if you have any questions please let me know and I'd be happy to assist.

https://helpcenter.netwrix.com/bundle/AccessAnalyzer_12.0/page/Content/EnterpriseAuditor/Solutions/FileSystem/Collection/1-SEEK_System_Scans.htm

Thank you,
Ian Ranstrom
